TY  - JOUR
AU  - Franks, Julian
AU  - Mayer, Colin
AU  - Miyajima, Hideaki
T1  - The Ownership of Japanese Corporations in the 20th Century
PY  - 2014
Y1  - 2014/09/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhu018
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 27
IS  - 9
SP  - 2580
EP  - 2625
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Twentieth century Japan provides a remarkable laboratory for examining how an externally imposed institutional and regulatory intervention affects the ownership of corporations. In the first half of the century, Japan had weak legal protection but strong institutional arrangements. The institutions were dismantled after the war and replaced by a strong form of legal protection. This inversion resulted in a switch from Japan being a country in which equity markets flourished and ownership was dispersed in the first half of the century to one in which banks and companies dominated with interlocking shareholdings in the second half of the century.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhu018
ER  - 



