TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bond, Philip
AU  - Glode, Vincent
T1  - The Labor Market for Bankers and Regulators
PY  - 2014
Y1  - 2014/09/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hht132
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 27
IS  - 9
SP  - 2539
EP  - 2579
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We propose a labor market model in which agents with heterogenous ability levels choose to work as bankers or as financial regulators. When workers extract intrinsic benefits from working in regulation (such as public-sector motivation or human capital accumulation), our model jointly predicts that bankers are, on average, more skilled than regulators and their compensation is more sensitive to performance. During financial booms, banks draw the best workers away from the regulatory sector and misbehavior increases. In a dynamic extension of our model, young regulators accumulate human capital and the best ones switch to banking in mid-career.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hht132
ER  - 



